We recommended that the Management, thru the Local Chief Executive:
Require the Inventory Committee to determine the unit cost/value of PPE items found at the station in accordance with Item 6 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 and thereafter, instruct the Municipal Accountant to recognize and record the items with costs of P50,000.00 and above in the books of accounts.  On the other hand, the items with costs below the capitalization threshold shall be monitored in the registry maintained by the General Services Office;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to investigate what caused the unreconciled balances of the Buildings, Other Structures, Office Equipment, Information and Communication Technology Equipment, Communication Equipment, Medical Equipment, Other Machinery & Equipment, Motor Vehicles, Watercrafts, Furniture and Fixtures and Other Property, Plant and Equipment accounts in the financial statement and the inventory report, and to prepare the appropriate adjusting entries to reconcile them;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to reverse the journal entries previously made to derecognize the non-existent/missing PPE accounts, and PPE accounts to be transferred to other agencies in the amounts of P11,235,287.73 and P10,906,482.32, respectively;
Instruct the GSO-Designate to institute measures for the proper disposition of non-existing /missing properties in accordance with Items 7 & 8 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to take up the necessary accounting entries to recognize in the books of accounts the loss of PPE and, where appropriate, to set up the corresponding receivables from concerned accountable officers/personnel for the non-existing/missing PPEs with available record of accountability;
File a request for authority to the COA Audit Team prior to the derecognition of non-existing/missing PPEs without available records of accountability;
Coordinate with the head of the recipient agency for proper turnover of the assets to be transferred to them and effect the recording of these assets in their books of accounts;
Require the Inventory Committee to strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances of the LGU; and
Require the Inventory Committee to ensure the timely submission of the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant, and Equipment to facilitate the Audit Team's verification process and enable the conduct of additional audit procedures to validate the LGU’s reported PPE balance in its Statement of Financial Position.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Enjoin the Municipal Engineer, General Services Officer, and the Municipal Accountant to comply with the accounting and reporting guidelines prescribed under COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015 to ensure fair presentation of the Road Networks account in the financial statements;
Require the reconciliation of the list of inventory per Local Road Inventory Report and Road Map with those recorded in the Road Networks account. Thereafter, the preparation of the Local Road Network Report must be observed yearly;
Seek the assistance of the Municipal Assessor for the valuation of the lot component of the local road networks; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to provide adequate disclosure regarding the Road Network System in the Notes to Financial Statements using the format prescribed in COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015.

We recommended the following:
The Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary journal entries to remove from the books the PPE accounts that fall under the classification of semi-expendable items, with a net book value of P2,415,880.17, and close the related Accumulated Depreciation to the appropriate accounts;
The Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary journal entries to recognize the issued semi-expendable properties in CY 2024 to their appropriate semi-expendable expense account, amounting to P978,771.00;
The Municipal Accountant to ensure that succeeding purchases of properties with costs of P50,000.00 and above should be recognized as PPE, while tangible items with costs below the capitalization threshold should be recorded under the appropriate semi-expendable property account; and
The General Services Officer to prepare and maintain the required forms, registries, and reports in order to establish accountability over these items and to safeguard them from the risk of improper use and possible loss or theft.

We recommended that the Management undertake the following:
Require the LGU officials, who approved the payment of the overtime services despite the absence of an appropriation therefor, to refund the overtime pay totaling P606,482.74;
Ensure that overtime services are provided with an appropriation under the Personal Services budget of the Municipality;
Require the Municipal Budget Officer to stop the practice of charging expenditures against appropriations that are intended for other purposes or a specific purpose; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to appropriately record the payment of overtime services and ensure that it is supported with complete documentation.

We recommended that the Management implement corrective measures and/or conduct repairs on the noted scaling of road pavement in the Concreting of Farm to Market Road at Brgy. Tucalan Passing, Lasam, and Concreting of Farm to Market Road at Brgy. Nabannagan West to Tucalan Passing, Lasam projects.
Moreover, we required that the Management submit the Statement of Work Accomplished as of the date of estimated completion of the following infrastructure projects for the computation of Liquidated Damages due to the delays in its completion, to wit:
1. 	Concreting of Farm to Market Road (Zone 2, Brgy. Magsaysay, Lasam);
2. 	Concreting of Farm to Market Road (Zone 3, Brgy. Magsaysay, Lasam);
3. 	Concreting of Farm to Market Road (Sitio Butac, Brgy. Nabannagan West, Lasam);
4. 	Improvement of Level II Water System (Cabatacan West, Lasam); and
5. 	Construction of New Health Station (Brgy. Peru, Lasam).
Finally, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive enjoin the Municipal Engineering Office to supervise the implementation of the infrastructure projects to avoid any deficiency in the infrastructure projects of the LGU.

